Analysis of Perspectives on Abortion Through the Decades: Social and Political Influences

Anh Tu Pham

Introduction

Throughout history, abortion has always been a controversial topic and poses many challenges to society, medical field and politics. Opinions about abortion are not only personal, but are influenced by a range of factors – from culture and religion, to education and politics.
Why do some people support women's right to choose in abortion while others feel that it is an unacceptable action? Are there differences between populations based on race, sex or education level? And most importantly, how have these perspective changed over the decade?

Background¶

Abortion has a complicated history, with many viewing it through moral, religious or individual authority. While some argue that every woman has the right to make decisions about her body, others argue that this decisions should be limited. Although much progress has been made in reducing risks and improving the quality of health services, views on abortion have not changed much.

In this tutorial, we will¶
  • Explores changing attitudes about abortion over the decades.
  • Analyze differences between groups based on race, gender, political party, and academic background.
  • Pose and test assumptions about the influence of social and political factors on attitudes about abortion.
  • Use machine learning models to predict an individual's opinion based on their personal information.

Let's explore and gain insight into one of the most controversial topics in modern society.

Data Collection

Data Source¶

This data was collected from the overall social survey and was shared on Kaggle at the following address: Abortion Opinions in the General Social Survey. This is a survey conducted annually to gather information on public opinion and opinion on various social issues, including views on abortion.

Data description¶

The General Social Survey is a social survey conducted annually in the United States that collects information about the public's views, attitudes, and behaviors on a wide range of social issues. The data includes surveys from 1972.

Data Processing

Before we start analyzing the data, the first thing we need to do is clean and prepare the data. Raw data often contains many errors and is not uniform. To have an accurate and reliable view of the data, we need to preprocess it carefully.

Handling columns with a high percentage of missing data¶

Based on the percentage of missing data, we will remove columns with too high a missing rate, such as hispaniccat, relactiv, and hispanic.

In [75]:
# Drop columns with high percentage of missing values
columns_to_drop = ['hispaniccat', 'relactiv', 'hispanic']
data_cleaned = data.drop(columns=columns_to_drop)

# Check the shape of the cleaned data
data_cleaned.shape
Out[75]:
(64814, 16)

Data after being cleaned has 16 columns (compared to the original 19 columns).

Fill in the missing data¶

For columns with a low percentage of missing data, we will fill in the missing value. For numeric data, we will use the mean, and for category data, we will use the value that occurs most often.

In [76]:
# Fill missing values for numeric columns with the mean
numeric_columns = ['age', 'educ', 'pid']
for column in numeric_columns:
    mean_value = data_cleaned[column].mean()
    data_cleaned[column].fillna(mean_value, inplace=True)

# Fill missing values for categorical columns with the mode
categorical_columns = ['partyid']
for column in categorical_columns:
    mode_value = data_cleaned[column].mode()[0]
    data_cleaned[column].fillna(mode_value, inplace=True)

# Check if there are any missing values left
remaining_missing = data_cleaned.isnull().sum()
remaining_missing

Due to the nature of this data (regarding personal opinions), filling in the missing values may not accurately reflect the opinions of the respondents. A common choice in this case is to keep the missing data intact and deal with them during analysis, e.g. when plotting or building models.

Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, & ML

Analysis¶

First, we will conduct some simple statistical analysis to look at the relationship between several variables.

Hypothesis testing¶

We will test the hypothesis that there is a significant difference in the pro-abortion ratio (abany column) between men and women. To do this, we will use the independent t-test. Hypothesis:

  • H0: There is no difference between the percentage of men and women in supporting of abortion.
  • H1: There is a difference between the proportion of men and women in supporting of abortion.
In [87]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# Separate the data for males and females
male_data = data_cleaned[data_cleaned['sex'] == 1]['abany'].dropna()
female_data = data_cleaned[data_cleaned['sex'] == 0]['abany'].dropna()

# Conduct the independent t-test
t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(male_data, female_data)

t_stat, p_value
Out[87]:
(4.093100951647711, 4.265497497462698e-05)

The independent t test results show that:

  • Statistical value t is 4.0931
  • Statistical value p is 4.27e-05, means very small.

Since the p-value is smaller than the normal significance level (eg, 0.05), we reject the H0 hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant difference between the proportions in supporting of abortion among men and women.

Machine learning¶

We will build a machine learning model to predict views on abortion (abany) based on other factors such as age, gender, education level, and political party. We will use logistic regression model, since this is a binary classification problem.

First, we need to prepare the data: divide the data into training and test sets, then proceed to build the model.

Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

Summary of key findings¶

One of the most important findings from the data is that people with more education tend to be more supportive of abortion. There are several possible explanations for this:

  • People with more education can be exposed to a larger amount of information and from a wider variety of sources.
  • They may have a stronger critical side and approach the issue from a more scientific perspective.
  • Academic environments often encourage freedom of thought and personal choice.

In addition, Perspective on abortion are clearly influenced by political parties. This shows that the abortion issue is not only a medical issue but also a political one. This not only reflects differences in political thinking, but also shows the influence of culture and education within each party.

Policy proposal¶

Based on the above findings, we can make several policy recommendations:

  • Strengthening education about women's reproductive health and choice. This can help people take a more thoughtful look and make decisions based on accurate information.
  • Create communication campaigns to reduce polarization on the issue, by presenting information from both sides of the issue.
  • Work with representatives from political parties to reach a consensus on policy regarding abortion.
Limitations and future development directions¶

Although we have made important findings from the data, it should be noted that there are limitations to this analysis:

  • Data represents only some people and may not reflect the entire view of society.
  • The machine learning models we used may not reflect the full complexity of the problem.

In the future, we can expand this study by collecting more data from a variety of sources and using more advanced analytical methods.
